{
  "legislative_session": "20252026",
  "identifier": "AB2227",
  "title": "Farm labor contractors: surety bonds.",
  "from_organization": "~{\"classification\": \"lower\"}",
  "classification": [
    "bill"
  ],
  "subject": [
    "Farmlaborcontractors",
    "suretybonds"
  ],
  "abstracts": [
    {
      "note": "summary",
      "abstract": "Existing law requires a farm labor contractor to be licensed by the Labor Commissioner and to comply with specified employment laws applicable to farm labor contractors. Existing law prohibits the Labor Commissioner from issuing or renewing a license to act as a farm labor contractor unless specified requirements are met.\n\nExisting law requires an applicant for the issuance or renewal of a farm labor contractor license to have deposited with the Labor Commissioner a surety bond to be payable for, among other things, interest on wages and for any damages arising from violation of orders of the Industrial Welfare Commission and for any other monetary relief awarded to an agricultural worker as a result of a violation of specified employment laws. Existing law requires the amount of the surety bond to be based on the size of the person's annual payroll for all employees, and requires, for payrolls up to $500,000, a $25,000 bond, for payrolls of $500,000 to $2,000,000, a $50,000 bond, and for payrolls greater than $2,000,000, a $75,000 bond. Existing law requires the Labor Commissioner to require documentation of the size of the person's annual payroll for purposes of these provisions, as provided.\n\nThis bill would instead require the amount of the surety bond to be based on the size of the person's annual gross receipts for all employees. Specifically, the bill would require, for gross receipts up to $500,000, a $50,000 bond, for gross receipts of $500,000 to $2,000,000, a $100,000 bond, and for gross receipts greater than $2,000,000, a $150,000 bond. The bill would require the Labor Commissioner to require documentation of the size of the person's gross receipts for purposes of these provisions, as provided. The bill would require the Labor Commissioner to, among other things, include bond information on the public farm labor contractor license database, as described."
    }
  ],
